<span id="xix.iv.xl-p1"></span> <span class="c2"><span
id="xix.iv.xl-p1.1"></span>Chapter 40 \[XIX.\]—The Ignorance of the
Pelagians in Maintaining that the Knowledge of the Law Comes from God,
But that Love Comes from Ourselves.</span>

<span id="xix.iv.xl-p2"></span>It is no wonder that light shineth in
darkness, and the darkness comprehendeth it not. <span
id="fr_3178"></span>[3179](#fn_3178.md) In John’s Epistle the Light
declares, “Behold what manner of love the Father hath bestowed upon us,
that we should be called the sons of God.” <span
id="fr_3179"></span>[3180](#fn_3179.md) And in the Pelagian writings the
darkness says, “Love comes to us of our own selves.” Now, if they only
possessed the true, that is, Christian love, they would also know whence
they obtained possession of it; even as the apostle knew when he said,
“But we have received not the spirit of the world, but the Spirit which
is of God, that we might know the things that are freely given to us of
God.” <span id="fr_3180"></span>[3181](#fn_3180.md) John says, “God is
love.” <span id="fr_3181"></span>[3182](#fn_3181.md) And thus the Pelagians
affirm that they actually have God Himself, not from God, but from their
own selves! and although they allow that we have the knowledge of the
law from God, they will yet have it that love is from our very selves.
Nor do they listen to the apostle when he says, “Knowledge puffeth up,
but love edifieth.” <span id="fr_3182"></span>[3183](#fn_3182.md) Now what
can be more absurd, nay, what more insane and more alien from the very
sacredness of love itself, than to maintain that from God proceeds the
knowledge which, apart from love, puffs us up, while the love which
prevents the possibility of this infla<span id="page_461">p. 461</span>
<span id="xix.iv.xl-Page_461"></span>tion of knowledge springs from
ourselves? And again, when the apostle speaks of “the love of Christ as
surpassing knowledge,” <span id="fr_3183"></span>[3184](#fn_3183.md) what
can be more insane than to suppose that the knowledge which must be
subordinated to love comes from God, while the love which surpasses
knowledge comes from man? The true faith, however, and sound doctrine
declare that both graces are from God; the Scripture says, “From His
face cometh knowledge and understanding;” <span
id="fr_3184"></span>[3185](#fn_3184.md) and another Scripture says, “Love
is of God.” <span id="fr_3185"></span>[3186](#fn_3185.md) We read of “the
Spirit of wisdom and understanding.” <span
id="fr_3186"></span>[3187](#fn_3186.md) Also of “the Spirit of power, and
of love, and of a sound mind.” <span
id="fr_3187"></span>[3188](#fn_3187.md) But love is a greater gift than
knowledge; for whenever a man has the gift of knowledge, love is
necessary by the side of it, that he be not puffed up. For “love envieth
not, vaunteth not itself, is not puffed up.” <span
id="fr_3188"></span>[3189](#fn_3188.md)

